A. OVERVIEW

Hungary's telecommunications sector is undergoing radical transformation.
Out of sheer necessity, Hungary has been forced to move ahead with reform.
Failure to do so would have engendered wider implications in terms of general
economic development.

Since 1989, there has been slow but steady progress with respect to
liberalization and decentralization.  The government has even initiated
privatization of the telecom sector.  with the sale of the Hungarian
Telecommunications Company's (MATAV) shares to strategic investors.

This new direction has given rise to opportunities for foreign companies in
both voice and data transfer.  While MATAV is pushing forward with an
ambitious landline development program, the company and other businesses are
experimenting with new technology, especially wireless.

Hungary is in a hurry to modernize itself and get "on-line" with the West.
This is critical if Hungary hopes to stimulate economic development.  This
study provides a brief overview of Hungary's telecom sector, describing where
the country has come from and where it is going.  The study is organized as
follows:

