Other important legislation related to the telecom sector include the
Concession Law and the Frequency Management Act (discussed in this section).
Additionally, Parliament has grappled with a draft media law for over two
years which would have implications for broadcasting as well as investment in
the media sector.  A law is expected to be enacted by the end of 1994.

The AVRT was created by Parliament in 1992.  The AVRT's portfolio consists of
164 companies in which the state will maintain some form of interest.  With
the election of a new government in May 1994, the privatization agencies will
be consolidated under the Ministry of Finance later in the year.

Government decrees stipulate that 50 percent plus 1 share of MATAV must
remain in state ownership.  With the new government, this threshold is likely
to be decreased to 25 percent or lower.  The aim of the new government is to
accelerate privatization and to reduce government holdings.  Already, the
government is preparing a floatation in exchange for "compensation coupons."
Additionally, an offering is likely to occur for international institutional
investors at a later date.  It should also be noted that in November 1993,
the International Finance Corporation (IFC) and the European Bank for
Reconstruction & Development (EBRD) purchased 10 percent of MATAV's shares.
Following privatization and the establishment of the actual share price, the
IFC and EBRD now hold less than 3 percent.
